			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2023</a> keynote:</span><br><i>Coccinelle: Impact and Internals</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JuliaLawall.html">Julia Lawall</a></h2>
<ul><li>URL: <a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/details/sle-2023/22/Coccinelle-Impact-and-Internals">https://2023.splashcon.org/details/sle-2023/22/Coccinelle-Impact-and-Internals</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagM">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> The keynote’s subject is a program matching and transformation tool, and the main story is about transformation at scale in real codebases.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> Its headline evidence is long-term maintenance work on the Linux kernel (thousands of commits), i.e., evolution via automated refactorings/patches.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6b.html"><span class="tagL">T6B: Industrial</span></a><ul><li> The talk is grounded in industrial-scale practice (real-world adoption and sustained use on a flagship system).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It discusses tool internals and design decisions enabling these transformations, making tooling/infrastructure a major aspect.
</li></ul></li></ul>
